```java
import java.sql.*;

public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    try {
      // Connect to the MySQL database
      String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost/mydatabase";
      String username = "myusername";
      String password = "mypassword";
      Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, username, password);

      // Execute a SELECT query
      Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
      String query = "SELECT * FROM mytable";
      ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery(query);

      // Loop through the results and print each record
      while (rs.next()) {
        int id = rs.getInt("id");
        String name = rs.getString("name");
        Double price = rs.getDouble("price");
        System.out.println(id + " " + name + " " + price);
      }

      // Close the database connection
      conn.close();
    } catch (Exception e) {
      System.out.println(e.getMessage());
    }
  }
}
```

In the above example, after getting a connection to the MySQL database, a statement object is created to execute a SELECT query to retrieve all records from a table named "mytable". The executeQuery() method of the statement object is called to execute the query, and the ResultSet object returned by the method contains all the results.

A loop is then used to iterate through the ResultSet object using the next() method and print each record using the appropriate get*() method for each column of the table.

Finally, the connection to the database is closed using the close() method of the Connection object.
